WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
 So now we're going to build a Python Dictionary class.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:08.640
 And here is the code that we would put in our dictionary.

00:00:08.640 --> 00:00:12.760
 I kept the strings really short because of all the,

00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:16.080
 I want the examples to be pretty short and easy.

00:00:16.080 --> 00:00:16.920
 So what do we do?

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:20.020
 We create a dictionary and we use the, you know,

00:00:20.020 --> 00:00:22.960
 bracket square bracket operator to create a key.

00:00:22.960 --> 00:00:24.620
 It's a key value pair.

00:00:24.620 --> 00:00:28.200
 The key Z match it goes to catch phrase, we print it out.

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:30.960
 The dictionary Z goes to W,

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:33.360
 which is replacing catchphrase with W.

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:35.640
 'Cause if you overwrite the same key,

00:00:35.640 --> 00:00:39.600
 you have to put the same, you have to replace the value.

00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:41.400
 And then we're going to throw three more things.

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:46.400
 Y maps to B, C maps to capital C, and A maps to D.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:49.360
 That's just so that it's not sorted too badly.

00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:50.960
 And then I print it out.

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:54.680
 And then I print the length of it.

00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:58.040
 I do a get and with a default value of 404.

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:00.000
 So sometimes I get that for Z,

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.520
 I get the W and then for X is not there.

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:03.820
 So I get the 404.

00:01:03.820 --> 00:01:08.480
 Again, kind of an homage to the HTTP error code 404 not found.

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:10.280
 And then I use it right over a little for loop

00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:12.640
 for key and dict, et cetera.

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:14.440
 I can print the key value pairs out.

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:17.000
 We'll do the same thing in C.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.280
 And again, this is almost a perfect transformation, literally.

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:24.280
 We first create the dictionary with calling a new,

00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:28.560
 then we put the word catchphrase in the Z key,

00:01:28.560 --> 00:01:31.080
 then we print it, then we put a W in the Z key,

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:33.180
 which should override it, and we print that.

00:01:33.180 --> 00:01:37.280
 And then we set the Y key to be B, the C to be capital C,

00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:40.200
 the A to be capital D, and then we print that.

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:42.240
 And then we ask, how long is it?

00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:44.760
 And then we do a get to look up under the Z key

00:01:44.760 --> 00:01:46.200
 and the X key, one of which is there,

00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:47.240
 one of which is not there.

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:48.920
 And I get a null back in that situation.

00:01:48.920 --> 00:01:52.200
 I guess I was a little C like in my get code.

00:01:52.200 --> 00:01:57.120
 And then I dump it out and I do a struct DNode loop

00:01:57.120 --> 00:02:00.200
 go from the head until it's null and I print out the key

00:02:00.200 --> 00:02:03.520
 and the value from each of those dictionary nodes.

00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:05.540
 And then I delete it at the end.

00:02:05.540 --> 00:02:08.020
 So this is the code.

00:02:08.020 --> 00:02:12.000
 Now again, notice we don't know much about looking things up.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:13.960
 We don't know how the length is maintained.

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:16.280
 We don't know how the static and dynamic allocation

00:02:16.280 --> 00:02:17.500
 is going to happen.

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:20.760
 We now have a contract with a bunch of library code

00:02:20.760 --> 00:02:23.360
 that is going to implement this dictionary object for us

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:27.240
 and do all of them memory manipulation on our behalf.

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:29.740
 Again, we start with the basic stuff.

00:02:29.740 --> 00:02:30.880
 The big thing we're going to do

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:32.760
 is we're going to not just have a value.

00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:34.160
 It looks a lot like a linked list.

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:35.500
 We're going to have a key value pair.

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:37.960
 The py dict has a head and a tail and a count,

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:39.680
 just like the py list.

00:02:39.680 --> 00:02:42.500
 And if you look at the constructor,

00:02:42.500 --> 00:02:45.400
 it's pretty much like the constructor for the list.

00:02:45.400 --> 00:02:50.120
 We allocate the dict py dict structure

00:02:50.120 --> 00:02:52.480
 and we set the head and tail to null to indicate empty.

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:54.360
 And we set the count to zero and we're done.

00:02:54.360 --> 00:02:55.560
 And the same with the del.

00:02:55.560 --> 00:02:59.560
 The del is very much like the linked list del.

00:02:59.560 --> 00:03:01.440
 Because we've allocated the key, the key

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:03.640
 is also going to be a dynamically allocated

00:03:03.640 --> 00:03:05.360
 pointer to a character array.

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:07.880
 So we got a free curr key along with curr value.

00:03:07.880 --> 00:03:09.640
 But then everything else is the same.

00:03:09.640 --> 00:03:13.520
 We preload the next value, then we free curr,

00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:15.080
 then we move to the next value.

00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:16.640
 And then when it's all said and done,

00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:19.800
 we free self, which is the py dict value.

00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:22.440
 When it's all said and done, we can call the new

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:26.200
 and then we can set a key, like catchphrase.

00:03:26.200 --> 00:03:29.680
 And the key thing there is the key and value

00:03:29.680 --> 00:03:33.760
 are both malloced bits of memory.

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:36.680
 Just like before we had the text,

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:38.880
 which was a malloced bit of memory and copied

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:40.240
 and we had to free it.

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:41.880
 But now we just have two things.

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:44.120
 And so the key and the value are two things

00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:46.320
 that are going to be malloced and then copied

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:47.520
 into the malloced area.

00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:49.120
 So some methods for you to build.

00:03:49.120 --> 00:03:51.560
 The lens should be pretty easy.

00:03:51.560 --> 00:03:53.760
 Similarly, we have a print that's going to be pretty

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:58.520
 and I want you to match exactly the output of the Python.

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:02.800
 And so it turns out that we can make a method called find,

00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:07.200
 which returns a DNode rather than get returns a string

00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:09.400
 and find returns a DNode.

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:14.400
 And then we can use find both in get and in put.

00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:17.600
 Now we use it pretty much in get to go find it

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:21.680
 and then return the value because we have the key.

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:24.240
 We look up find it by key and then return the value.

00:04:24.240 --> 00:04:27.760
 So that's pretty easy to do the get once you have find.

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:30.120
 So the find is a for loop where you're going to go

00:04:30.120 --> 00:04:31.240
 and you're going to find it.

00:04:31.240 --> 00:04:33.680
 And if you find it, you're going to send it back.

00:04:33.680 --> 00:04:36.080
 And if you're not, you're going to send a null back.

00:04:36.080 --> 00:04:38.520
 Now you better check if it's null, right?

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:42.760
 Including in the get, you've got to check if it's null.

00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:44.440
 But then in the put, what you do is

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:47.880
 you look up the old one with pydict_find.

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:51.040
 And if you get one, if old is not equal to null,

00:04:51.040 --> 00:04:55.320
 then you're updating the key, updating the value for the key.

00:04:55.320 --> 00:04:56.760
 And if not, you're adding it.

00:04:56.760 --> 00:04:59.200
 Now the thing about the else clause here

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:01.640
 is it looks a lot like a linked list.

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:04.120
 Because really if you look at this thing,

00:05:04.120 --> 00:05:06.640
 it is a linked list.

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:08.440
 It's just there's two values in each one.

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:09.800
 We're not doing anything magical.

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:12.240
 Now more advanced dictionary implementations

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:15.240
 might use hash maps or binary trees or other things

00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:17.720
 like that, like that we're in chapter six that we

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:19.160
 didn't talk too much about.

00:05:19.160 --> 00:05:21.240
 But for now, we're just going to make our dictionary

00:05:21.240 --> 00:05:22.800
 be a linked list.

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:25.040
 But instead of just a value, it's a key and a value.

00:05:25.040 --> 00:05:26.880
 So we can look it up by key.

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:29.080
 And so we're not doing too much tricky stuff

00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:34.560
 to make our dictionary really by just adding a bit to a list.

00:05:34.560 --> 00:05:37.240
 So let's just take a look at how this

00:05:37.240 --> 00:05:42.520
 is going to work in sort of the real world as it runs.

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:44.720
 So remember, we have kind of the dictionary

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:47.480
 itself, which is a head and a tail and a count.

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:49.120
 And then we have the dictionary nodes,

00:05:49.120 --> 00:05:51.320
 which is our key and value.

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:53.420
 And the next one, now the key and the value

00:05:53.420 --> 00:05:54.760
 are not the actual strings.

00:05:54.760 --> 00:05:55.840
 They're just pointers to strings,

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:57.640
 which means we're going to have to use malloc.

00:05:57.640 --> 00:05:59.400
 When we get a key and we get a value,

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:04.400
 we're going to have to malloc and copy both of those things.

00:06:04.400 --> 00:06:07.520
 So if we start and we see pydict_new,

00:06:07.520 --> 00:06:10.840
 we're going to get a dictionary with head and tail

00:06:10.840 --> 00:06:12.880
 that point to null.

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:18.120
 And then if we add catchphrase, well, we allocate the z.

00:06:18.120 --> 00:06:21.320
 We allocate and copy the key z.

00:06:21.320 --> 00:06:25.600
 And we allocate and copy the value and put those in key.

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:29.000
 And then next is null and head and tail point to this thing.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:30.480
 So we've allocated three things.

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:33.040
 We've allocated a DNode.

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:38.680
 And we've allocated two character arrays using malloc.

00:06:38.680 --> 00:06:42.640
 So then let's say we're going to run the next line of code,

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:46.800
 which is setting the key z to w.

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:51.640
 Now when you're in the put code, you go and you call find.

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:53.480
 And you see that there is a thing.

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:55.280
 There is already a z in there.

00:06:55.280 --> 00:06:57.040
 So what you've got to do is you've

00:06:57.040 --> 00:06:59.260
 got to replace catchphrase.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:05.800
 So you actually, before you go and make a new value,

00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:07.680
 you then copy w into it.

00:07:07.680 --> 00:07:09.440
 You want to free the old stuff.

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:14.280
 And so you tend to free the value that was in there before.

00:07:14.280 --> 00:07:17.600
 And then you malloc and copy in for the new value.

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:19.480
 So if you're done, at the end of this,

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:22.400
 you will have catchphrase somewhere in magic free space.

00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:26.400
 We don't know how C does magic free space, but it does do it.

00:07:26.400 --> 00:07:29.080
 So at the end of the second put, you

00:07:29.080 --> 00:07:31.320
 still have one entry, but the value

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:33.680
 has been changed from pointing at catchphrase

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:35.680
 to pointing at w.

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:37.640
 Then we add y equals b.

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:40.340
 Well, you do a find and there is no y key.

00:07:40.340 --> 00:07:42.240
 So now it's more like a linked list.

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:46.280
 You create a new D node and you append it to the end,

00:07:46.280 --> 00:07:47.880
 just like in a linked list.

00:07:47.880 --> 00:07:50.740
 And then you save the key and point key at it.

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:53.240
 And then you save the value into new malloc space

00:07:53.240 --> 00:07:54.760
 and then point value at that.

00:07:54.760 --> 00:07:58.280
 And then we go to the next one, where we point C,

00:07:58.280 --> 00:08:00.280
 that we don't find C in there.

00:08:00.280 --> 00:08:03.320
 So we create a new D node.

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:07.240
 And then we do a malloc of the key and a malloc of the value.

00:08:07.240 --> 00:08:09.440
 And we point to those and then copy the data

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:11.360
 into those two malloced areas.

00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:14.180
 And then point key and value at those malloced areas.

00:08:14.180 --> 00:08:16.720
 And you can kind of see that this is really, at this point,

00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:20.380
 unless we find the key in there already,

00:08:20.380 --> 00:08:22.220
 it's just a linked list that happens

00:08:22.220 --> 00:08:25.480
 to have two character arrays that are dynamically

00:08:25.480 --> 00:08:28.520
 allocated and copied, one for key, one for value.

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:30.520
 That was a bunch of object orientation.

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:32.800
 It was kind of a walk down the path

00:08:32.800 --> 00:08:35.120
 that Guido van Rossum took probably

00:08:35.120 --> 00:08:37.800
 in the first few weeks of him building the string

00:08:37.800 --> 00:08:39.560
 class, list class, and dictionary class.

00:08:39.560 --> 00:08:43.440
 Chances are good, he built something very, very similar.

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:45.680
 And then he's like, OK, now I've got to make this better.

00:08:45.680 --> 00:08:47.720
 But if I was just writing this thing,

00:08:47.720 --> 00:08:49.480
 he'd probably just type this out.

00:08:49.480 --> 00:08:51.760
 It's kind of pretty for computer scientists

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:54.960
 who've been doing algorithm data structures their whole lives.

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:57.640
 It's like, well, why don't I just make a class that does this?

00:08:57.640 --> 00:09:01.320
 Now that I've got sort of an object oriented universe,

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:04.080
 let me hide all of the dynamic memory.

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:05.800
 And that's really what we're doing.

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:08.760
 We're hiding the dynamic memory and the implementation details

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:12.400
 and all the for loops and while loops are being hidden.

00:09:12.400 --> 00:09:13.200
 They're important.

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:15.200
 And if you were to look at the source code

00:09:15.200 --> 00:09:17.800
 to str, list, and dict in Python,

00:09:17.800 --> 00:09:19.880
 you'd see they're allocating and reallocating.

00:09:19.880 --> 00:09:22.800
 They're doing it a lot more cleverly than what we did.

00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:24.880
 You don't want to call realloc too many times,

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:26.920
 but for now it works.

00:09:26.920 --> 00:09:29.000
 We're doing small stuff.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:31.280
 There is an infinite number.

00:09:31.280 --> 00:09:34.640
 There's an infinite array of optimizations

00:09:34.640 --> 00:09:38.360
 to make all of this way faster and more impressive.

00:09:38.360 --> 00:09:44.160
 But that's really for another time.

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:49.960
 So we've kind of got the idea of the baby steps

00:09:49.960 --> 00:09:53.680
 from a procedural language with pointers, structures,

00:09:53.680 --> 00:09:55.800
 and dynamic memory allocation.

00:09:55.800 --> 00:09:58.960
 How you would take the step using those underlying things

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:03.120
 in a procedural language to build basic objects

00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:05.840
 and support those objects, perhaps as you're building

00:10:05.840 --> 00:10:08.240
 a new language like Python.

